# Goals

## Relay-G1 Relay Orchestrator executes serial agent flows with baton passing and gate enforcement
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** AgentConfig-G1

- [x] Flow specs define ordered steps with professions, gates, loops, and branches
- [x] Only one agent holds the baton at any time
- [x] Orchestrator enforces tool availability per profession
- [x] Orchestrator routes handoffs deterministically without LLM coordination cost
- [x] Loop bounds and error routing prevent infinite cycles

The Orchestrator is pure deterministic code (Rust), not an LLM. It reads Flow specs, manages the Pipeline state machine, and routes batons. This eliminates token spend on coordination and makes routing predictable.
---

## Relay-G2 Handoff Protocol compresses context between agents, achieving ~5× token savings vs parallel multi-agent
**Status:** implemented
**Tags:** stack:backend
**Depends on:** AgentConfig-G1, Relay-G1

- [x] Handoff documents exclude raw chat history
- [x] Handoff documents include: summary, decisions, open questions, spec updates, work product, context pointers
- [x] Context scoping filters specs to only those relevant to the receiving profession
- [x] Each agent receives ≤9k tokens at spawn (Soul + relevant Specs + Handoff)
- [x] Agents pull additional context on demand via tools, not via push

The Handoff Protocol is the core token-efficiency mechanism. By discarding chat history and summarizing work product, agents start each turn with minimal context. Parallel multi-agent systems suffer O(N×K) token overhead; relay reduces this to O(sum of scoped contexts).
---

